{
  "doc_id": "29810",
  "text": "Five studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] used IHC to determine Ezrin status, whereas one study [CITATION_6] used RT-PCR and one study [CITATION_7] used both IHC and RT-PCR determinations. Two studies [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] ) used more than 10% cut-off Ezrin positivity, whereas two studies [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] used more than 1% cut-off Ezrin positivity and two studies [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] used more than 0% cut-off Ezrin positivity. The antibodies to be used in each study are not the same (Table 1 ). The cutoff of 90% necrosis to separate responders from nonresponders was used by three studies [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] , whereas one study [CITATION_17] used the cutoff of 95% necrosis and one studies [CITATION_18] used the Huvos grading system. The incidence of histologic response to chemotherapy ranged from 36% to 53.1%, and 2-year mortality rates ranged between 20% and 61.8% across the eligible studies. Both the chemotherapy response rates and 2-year mortality differed significantly across studies (P < 0.01 for both). This may be due to differences in the case mix of the study populations (e.g., grade and stage) and/or the therapies used.",
